snippet: Interpol said that two passengers known to have used stolen passports to board the Malaysia Airlines jet that vanished were unlikely to be linked to terrorist groups.
abstract: International authorities say that Pouria Nourmohammadi Mehrdad and Seyed Mohammed Reza Delavar, Iranians known to have used stolen passports to board the missing Malaysia Airlines jet, are unlikely to be linked to terrorist groups; assessment echoes that of Malaysian police.

byline.original: By THOMAS FULLER and JANE PERLEZ
byline.contributor: Thomas Fuller reported from Sepang, and Jane Perlez from Pattaya, Thailand. Alan Cowell contributed reporting from London, Nicola Clark from Paris, and Thomas Erdbrink from Tehran.

lead_paragraph: Interpol said that two passengers known to have used stolen passports to board the Malaysia Airlines jet that vanished were unlikely to be linked to terrorist groups.

headline.main: Stolen Passports on Plane Not Seen as Terror Link
headline.print_headline: Stolen Passports on Plane Not Seen as Terror Link
